<body>
    <h1>Trie Data Structure: A Comprehensive Guide</h1>

    <section>
        <h2>Introduction to Tries</h2>
        <p>A <strong>Trie</strong> (pronounced "try") is a specialized tree-like data structure that is particularly efficient for storing and searching strings. The name comes from the word "<em>retrieval</em>," highlighting its primary use case in information retrieval systems.</p>

        <p>Unlike binary search trees where nodes store keys associated with that node, in a trie, the position of a node defines the key with which it is associated. This makes tries especially useful for operations involving strings, such as autocomplete systems, spell checkers, and IP routing.</p>

        <div class="note">
            <p><strong>Key Characteristics:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Also known as <em>prefix tree</em> or <em>digital tree</em></li>
                <li>Nodes don't store complete keys - keys are represented by the path from the root</li>
                <li>Common prefixes among keys are shared, saving space</li>
                <li>Provides O(m) time complexity for search, insert, and delete operations where m is the length of the key</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Trie Structure and Properties</h2>

        <h3>Basic Structure</h3>
        <p>A trie consists of nodes that typically have the following components:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Children:</strong> An array or hash table of child nodes (usually one per possible character)</li>
            <li><strong>End-of-word marker:</strong> A boolean indicating if this node completes a valid word</li>
            <li><strong>Optional:</strong> Value associated with the word (for dictionary implementations)</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="visualization">
            <p><strong>Visual Representation of a Simple Trie:</strong></p>
            <pre>
                (root)
                /   \
               t     a
              /       \
             o         t
            / \         \
           d  m         e
          /    \         \
         (dog)  (tom)     (ate)
            </pre>
        </div>

        <h3>Key Properties</h3>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Prefix Sharing:</strong> All descendants of a node have a common prefix of the string associated with that node.</li>
            <li><strong>Root Node:</strong> Represents an empty string.</li>
            <li><strong>Path from Root:</strong> Each path from the root to a marked node represents a stored string.</li>
            <li><strong>Branching Factor:</strong> Determined by the alphabet size (26 for English letters, 256 for ASCII, etc.).</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Trie Operations</h2>

        <h3>1. Insertion</h3>
        <p>To insert a word into a trie:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>Start at the root node</li>
            <li>For each character in the word:
                <ul>
                    <li>If the current node has a child node with that character, move to it</li>
                    <li>Otherwise, create a new node and add it as a child</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Mark the last node as the end of the word</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="example">
            <p><strong>Example: Inserting "cat" into an empty trie</strong></p>
            <ol>
                <li>Create root node</li>
                <li>Add 'c' child to root</li>
                <li>Add 'a' child to 'c'</li>
                <li>Add 't' child to 'a'</li>
                <li>Mark 't' node as end-of-word</li>
            </ol>
        </div>

        <h3>2. Search</h3>
        <p>To search for a word in a trie:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>Start at the root node</li>
            <li>For each character in the word:
                <ul>
                    <li>If the current node has a child with that character, move to it</li>
                    <li>Otherwise, the word doesn't exist in the trie</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Check if the last node is marked as end-of-word</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>3. Deletion</h3>
        <p>To delete a word from a trie:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>Search for the word (if not found, return)</li>
            <li>If the word is found:
                <ul>
                    <li>Unmark the end-of-word flag</li>
                    <li>If the node has no children, delete it and recurse upwards</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Time and Space Complexity</h2>

        <table border="1" cellpadding="8" cellspacing="0" style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse;">
            <tr>
                <th>Operation</th>
                <th>Time Complexity</th>
                <th>Notes</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Insertion</td>
                <td>O(m)</td>
                <td>m = length of the string</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Search</td>
                <td>O(m)</td>
                <td>Faster than hash tables for many operations</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Deletion</td>
                <td>O(m)</td>
                <td>May require cleanup of unused nodes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Prefix Search</td>
                <td>O(m + k)</td>
                <td>m = prefix length, k = number of matches</td>
            </tr>
        </table>

        <div class="note">
            <p><strong>Space Complexity:</strong> O(α * m * n)</p>
            <p>Where α is the alphabet size, m is average string length, and n is number of strings. While tries can be space-efficient for shared prefixes, they can consume more memory than hash tables for large alphabets or when prefixes aren't shared.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Applications of Tries</h2>

        <h3>1. Autocomplete Systems</h3>
        <p>Tries excel at prefix-based queries, making them ideal for autocomplete implementations in search engines, IDEs, and mobile keyboards.</p>

        <h3>2. Spell Checkers</h3>
        <p>Tries can quickly determine if a word exists in a dictionary and suggest corrections by exploring similar paths.</p>

        <h3>3. IP Routing (Longest Prefix Matching)</h3>
        <p>Network routers use compressed tries (radix trees) to efficiently find the longest prefix match for IP addresses.</p>

        <h3>4. Word Games</h3>
        <p>Games like Scrabble or Boggle benefit from tries for validating words and finding possible moves.</p>

        <h3>5. Genome Analysis</h3>
        <p>In bioinformatics, tries help with DNA sequence alignment and pattern matching.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Variations of Tries</h2>

        <h3>1. Compressed Trie (Radix Tree)</h3>
        <p>Nodes with only one child are merged with their parent to reduce space usage, trading some simplicity for efficiency.</p>

        <h3>2. Suffix Trie</h3>
        <p>Contains all suffixes of a given text, enabling efficient substring searches and used in full-text indices.</p>

        <h3>3. Ternary Search Trie</h3>
        <p>Each node has three children (less than, equal to, or greater than current character), offering a balance between BSTs and regular tries.</p>

        <h3>4. Double-Array Trie</h3>
        <p>Space-efficient implementation using two parallel arrays to represent the trie structure.</p>
    </section>

